entry.title: [mullet m2] Store profile id in field-by-field filling suggestions.
entry.content:
We want to add two new types of field-by-field filling:

1. Full name

2. Street name



However, differently from the current usages where the text rendered in

the suggestion is what is entered the field (Suggestion::main_text),

these two new suggestions will have different main text values, they

will work as follows:



- If the trigger field is not of name group a "Fill full name"

suggestion is added, it will be of PopupItemId::kFieldByFieldFilling

type and fill the FULL_NAME.

- If the trigger field is not of address group a "Fill address"

suggestion is added, it will also be field-by-field filling and it

will fill the STREET_ADDRESS information (if it exists, naturally).



This change is a noop and makes it possible for the two suggestions

above to be introduced in a follow up.



I will also start using this value in the follow up CL.

entry.title: Revert "SimpleCache: fix crash w/iterator entry doom concurrent w/bulk doom"
entry.content:
This reverts commit d6b97570330071cd3070af3d0cbce20ac1866bce.



Reason for revert: This causes a bad regression for CachedStorage, since it can Doom entries which are opened by name simultaneously with being iterated over, which affects Google Docs Offline. I have proper fix in progress, but it feels too risky for M120, and the original bug had pretty low incidence rate[1], so rolling this back to prep for backport. Then this will be reapplied and a proper fix landed for M121.



[1] Ben, any chance my judgement on that is skewed by the experiment involved?



Original change's description:

> SimpleCache: fix crash w/iterator entry doom concurrent w/bulk doom

>

> The trouble was that entries opened via hash were not kept track of in active_entries_ until the open succeeded, and so the usual rules of letting an entry object take care of its own doom if it is around was not followed if a mass doom happened in that window.

>

> So change the code to add the fresh entry to active_entries_ during open-by-hash just as it would be during a regular open. This does mean that active_entries_ sometimes has entries that don't have their key set yet, so the key in SimpleEntryImpl and SimpleSynchronousEntry was changed to be explicitly an optional, to make sure we never get confused --- it should be set by the time it's every user-visible, but now there will be angry absl::optional CHECKs if we screw up. (This also can avoid some confusion between empty key and key not set).

>

do a lexicographical comparison of member variables. Use default

operator<=>(), aka the spaceship operator, is used if equality plus

ordering comparisons are needed.

entry.title: [iOS] Remove redundant sign-in error in consistency promo
entry.content:
Any failure or cancel during the AuthenticationFlow execution triggers

an generic error alert when signing in from the bottom sheet.

Since an alert has been added for managed account in this sign-in flow

which allows the user to cancel sign-in, the generic error shows upon

the cancel action, which is not intended and confusing for the user.



Besides,

- An error alert should already be triggered upon failure inside the

AuthenticationFlow, making this error alert redundant for failures.

- This error handling is inconsistent with other sign-in UIs which

don't show any standalone error upon AuthenticationFlow completion.



This CL removes the generic error alert and adds an EGTest to ensure

that the generic error alert is not shown when cancelling sign-in in

the mentioned case.



It also updates the name of the histogram enum used to explicit that

cancel and failure are handled in the same bucket.



Bug: 1501323

entry.title: [Hub] add pane LoadHints
entry.content:
Add basic support for signalling panes about the state of the Hub's

visibility in the form of LoadHints.

* Other panes are WARM



If the Hub is invisible:

* All panes are COLD



The changes to the active Pane happen immediately upon focus or Hub

visibility changing. The remaining Panes are posted to spread any

cost across time and minimize jank.

entry.title: Replace CreditCardAccessManager::Accessor with a callback
entry.content:
CreditCardAccessManager::Accessor is an interface that only defines

a single function OnCreditCardFetched(). It is used to notify callers

once fetching a credit card has finished and currently implemented by

BrowserAutofillManager and CreditCardAccessoryController.



This CL removes this interface and instead defines

using OnCreditCardFetchedCallback =

base::OnceCallback
const CreditCard*)>;



FetchCreditCard()'s base::WeakPtr parameter is replaced by an

OnCreditCardFetchedCallback instead.



This is preferable for a few reasons:

- It makes it explicit that the callback is only invoked once.

- It makes it more obvious on the caller-side what function will be

invoked when the credit card is fetched. E.g.

credit_card_access_manager_->FetchCreditCard(

credit_card, weak_ptr_factory_.GetWeakPtr());

becomes

credit_card_access_manager_->FetchCreditCard(

credit_card,

base::BindOnce(&BrowserAutofillManager::OnCreditCardFetched,

weak_ptr_factory_.GetWeakPtr()));

- It makes it easier for future CLs to move logic away from the BAM.

This motivated this CL. See go/autofill-filling-api-refactoring.

- It's the more C++-y way to define FetchCreditCard().



Test tests become a bit longer, since every call to FetchCreditCard()

requires an additional line due to the base::BindOnce() now.
